  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "aaYNC5vDzq3p03FB0ln8uqRq91w=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nThe Bee Reactor Adapter uses a **manifest-as-reference pattern**: the feed SOC contains only a 32-byte pointer to encrypted manifest bytes uploaded via `/bytes`, not the manifest itself.\n\n## Evidence\n\nWrite path:\n1. Serialize manifest JSON\n2. Encrypt with app-layer AES-256-GCM\n3. Upload to `/bytes` \u2192 receive 64-char content hash\n4. Write ONLY the 32-byte hash into the feed via `makeFeedWriter().uploadReference(stamp, reference)` (72-byte SOC)\n\nRead path reverses: read feed \u2192 get hash \u2192 download from `/bytes` \u2192 decrypt \u2192 parse.\n\nbee-js offers two feed writer modes:\n- `uploadPayload(stamp, data)` \u2014 writes data <= 4096 bytes directly into the SOC\n- `uploadReference(stamp, reference)` \u2014 writes just a 32-byte reference\n\n## Why it matters\n\nThis pattern keeps feed SOCs tiny and fixed-size regardless of manifest size, and decouples encryption/versioning of manifest bytes from feed indexing. It's how every drive, doc, and user manifest is persisted.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
